This is knowledge passed down through generations ,thatâ€™s exactly why he mentions his grandparents. History didnâ€™t start yesterday. Liberia was largely founded by Black Americans who returned after slavery, and that is a documented fact, not an opinion.
So yes, this could trace back to the 1800s, when places like Ohio were not what they are today. Trying to mock that history or dismiss it as ignorance is dishonest.
The real issue is that many Americans are uncomfortable accepting the truth that their descendants came from Africa and were enslaved. You can hide behind labels like â€œindigenous thisâ€ or â€œindigenous that,â€ but it doesnâ€™t change history. Denial doesnâ€™t erase facts. It only exposes how desperate people are to avoid them.

Liberia was founded in the early 1800s by formerly enslaved Black Americans (often called Americo-Liberians) who were resettled from the United States, mainly through the American Colonization Society.
The first settlers arrived in 1822
Liberia declared independence in 1847
These settlers brought American culture with them: Christianity, Western clothing, English, U.S.-style government, and social structures

Liberia was not mostly made up of returned Black Americans in terms of population.
Indigenous African ethnic groups (Kpelle, Bassa, Kru, Gio, Mano, Grebo, etc.) were already living there & vastly outnumbered the settlers.
Americo-Liberians never exceeded about 5% of the population, even at their peak.
However, they controlled political power, land, and government for over 100 years.
Thatâ€™s why people sometimes feel like Liberia was â€œAmericanâ€bcoz power, education, and official culture were dominated by Americo-Liberians, not because they were the majority.
